{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568372"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20058"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20058"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.04,0.04,0.06,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12837"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3819"},{"type":"tags","id":"4789"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of a painful area around her anus. She reports occasional bleeding after bowel movements but denies any change in bowel habit, weight loss, or systemic symptoms. Her medical history includes a renal transplant eight years ago for which she takes immunosuppressive medications. She is a reformed smoker with a 20 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Perineal examination reveals an ulcerating lesion approximately 2 cm in diameter at the anal verge with raised, rolled edges and induration of the surrounding tissue (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anal squamous cell carcinoma","Perianal Crohn disease","Condyloma acuminatum","Perianal abscess","Ulcerated haemorrhoid"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows an ulcerating lesion with raised, rolled edges at the anal verge, which is highly suspicious for anal cancer. This patient has several risk factors that increase her likelihood of developing \u003Cstrong\u003Eanal squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Most importantly, she is immunosuppressed due to anti-rejection medications for her renal transplant. Immunosuppression significantly increases the risk of human papillomavirus (HPV)-related malignancies, including anal cancer. Additionally, her history of smoking is another established risk factor for anal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerianal Crohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with multiple fistulous tracts, skin tags, and fissures rather than a single ulcerating lesion with raised edges. Patients usually have other gastrointestinal symptoms related to Crohn disease, which are absent in this case. The appearance of the lesion is not consistent with the knife-cut ulcers or fistulae typically seen in Crohn disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondyloma acuminatum\u003C/strong\u003E (genital warts) presents as cauliflower-like growths rather than ulcerating lesions. While also caused by HPV and more common in immunosuppressed patients, condylomata are typically multiple, exophytic, and non-ulcerated. They may occasionally become quite large in immunosuppressed patients but would not have the ulceration and rolled edges seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerianal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute pain, erythema, swelling, and often systemic symptoms such as fever. The lesion would appear as a fluctuant, erythematous swelling rather than an ulcerating lesion with rolled edges. The two-month history without progression to spontaneous drainage also makes an abscess unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerated haemorrhoid\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with bright red bleeding, particularly during defecation. While haemorrhoids can become thrombosed and ulcerated, they would not have the characteristic raised, rolled edges seen in this lesion. Haemorrhoids also tend to be soft, vascular swellings rather than indurated lesions. The induration and rolled edges strongly suggest a malignant process rather than a benign haemorrhoidal condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe definitive diagnosis of anal cancer requires histopathological confirmation through biopsy. Management typically involves chemoradiation therapy, with the Nigro protocol (5-fluorouracil, mitomycin C, and radiation) being the standard of care for most cases of anal squamous cell carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anal cancer commonly presents as a painful ulcerating lesion at the anal margin.","Human papillomavirus (HPV) infection is the most significant risk factor for anal cancer.","Immunosuppression increases the risk of HPV-related malignancies including anal cancer.","Biopsy is essential for definitive diagnosis of suspicious anal lesions."],"references":["Gardner IH, Watson KM. Diagnosis and Treatment of Anal Squamous Cell Carcinoma. Dis Colon Rectum 2020; 63: 1358\u2013362"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20058"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21737"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21737"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/w3w8nQOyIpaSQuMbIq1gNXG2y3KCPd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/w3w8nQOyIpaSQuMbIq1gNXG2y3KCPd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":502,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T23:26:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T23:28:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12837"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":nu